# FULL SPECTRUM: AI Orchestration, Sovereign Systems, and Cognitive Architecture

### A university-level course in 6 units, 24 modules
### Condensed seed document — expand per module as needed

---

## UNIT 1: POSTURE
*Before you touch any tool, learn how to think.*

### Module 1.1 — Systems Before Tasks

You are not a problem-solver. You are a system-reader. The bug fixed three times is not three bugs — it is one system you haven't read yet. Before asking "how do I fix this?" ask "what kind of thing is this?" That question, asked first every time, separates people who react from people who govern.

Two cognitive modes exist: governor and worker. Governor mode decides what tasks should exist. Worker mode executes tasks. The universal failure is doing worker thinking when governor thinking is needed — solving the immediate problem when you should be questioning whether it's the right problem.

**Exercise:** Given a failing software feature, students must produce two documents: a worker-mode bug fix AND a governor-mode system analysis. Compare what each finds. The gap is the lesson.

### Module 1.2 — The File Is the Memory

The single biggest failure mode in AI-assisted work is treating the conversation as the memory system. Conversations end. Context windows close. The model forgets. The foundational inversion: put the memory in the artifact. The file carries the reasoning, the decisions, the history, the rules. The conversation is scaffolding. The file is the building.

Cold-handoff is the quality gate: can a total stranger — human or AI — pick up this file with zero briefing and participate correctly? If yes, the file is complete. If no, the file is incomplete. Every minute of onboarding time is a measurement of incompleteness.

**Exercise:** Students write a project specification, then hand it cold to a classmate who has never seen it. The classmate attempts to execute from the file alone. Debrief: what was missing? That's the incompleteness score.

### Module 1.3 — Prime Before Evidence

The same information lands differently depending on what mental model was running when it arrived. An unprimed reader finds content. A primed reader finds anomalies. The anomalies are always more valuable.

Sequence: build the mental model first, load the evidence second, compare the two third. The comparison is the work. Never send the files first.

**Exercise:** Half the class receives a codebase with no briefing. The other half receives a one-paragraph threat model first, then the same codebase. Compare findings. The primed group will find categories of issue the unprimed group structurally cannot.

