## UNIT 3: DELIVERY
*How to get code from AI to human reliably.*

### Module 3.1 — Fragment-First Development

One document. For you and the AI. The human's job: paste code into an editor in order. The AI's job: deliver code in small, numbered chunks (mini-blocks) with no text after the code fence. One-word commands control flow: GO, NEXT, VIOLATION, FENCE, BREAK.

The block footer is where all thinking goes: what the block provides, gate test, install instructions, what must never change, ring notes (criticality classification), what the next block needs to know, breadcrumb (why this works the way it does).

The ring notes classify every piece of code: Ring 0 = constitutional core, everything depends on it. Ring 1 = protocol surface, shared interfaces. Ring 2 = leaf logic, safe to change freely. This is inter-session memory for a system that has none.

**Exercise:** Students use FFD to build a small working application across three sessions with three different AI instances. The third instance must succeed using only the block footers from the first two. If it can't, the footers are incomplete.

### Module 3.2 — The Human Bus

In zero-infrastructure multi-instance work, the human is the transport layer, state manager, debugger, and timing mechanism. Copy-paste is not a limitation to be overcome. It is a first-class systems primitive — transparent, vendor-agnostic, debuggable, resilient.

Every message between AI instances travels through the human. The human can inspect every signal in transit, catch drift, and intervene at timing points no automated system could identify.

**Exercise:** Students orchestrate a three-window workflow (Director, Builder, Reviewer) using only copy-paste transport. Then they run the same workflow through an automated pipeline. Compare: bug visibility, drift detection, recoverability. The manual version will catch issues the automated version misses.

